"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709028","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I provided on 24 November 2016 to Question number 53850.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2017-03-13T15:12:49.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709028/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709028/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-07","HIV Infection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to the UN programme on HIV/AIDS, published in June 2016, what discussions she has had with her international counterparts on the decline in global HIV funding by 13 per cent between 2014 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","66790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709029","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Government will continue to review the UK future trade policy. The Department for International Development and the Department for International Trade will continue to work together to decide how our future trading arrangements with developing countries can support sustainable development.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-03-14T17:16:49.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709029/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709029/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-07","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, pursuant to the Answer of 22 February 2017 to Question 64094, on trade agreements: sustainable development, if she will publish her Department's review of the UK's future trade policy.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","66937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709030","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-14","<p>Between 2011 and 2015, UKAID supported over five million girls in developing countries to gain an education. By the end of 2017, the flagship Girls’ Education Challenge will enable up to one million marginalised girls to benefit from an education of sufficient quality to help transform their lives.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-14T17:20:40.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709030/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709030/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-07","Developing Countries: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that girls in the poorest countries can access education.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","66941"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709031","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-14","<p>It is the family court’s overriding duty to treat the welfare of the child as its paramount consideration when deciding child arrangements. We are actively working with the judiciary to consider proposed amendments to Practice Direction 12J, which provides guidance to judges on making child arrangements in cases where domestic violence or abuse is alleged or admitted. Courts can already order that parental contact takes place only at a supervised centres, and only where contact will further the child’s welfare. These supervised centres have specially trained staff who carefully manage any potential risks to the child or other parent.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-14T17:16:28.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709031/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709031/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Family Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she is taking to help reduce avoidable child deaths as a result of unsafe child contact with a perpetrator of domestic abuse.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","66942"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709032","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>We announced the intention to amend the domestic violence evidence requirements in applications for legal aid in private family proceedings via a press notice. This included confirmation that we plan to remove the time limit on evidence of domestic violence and to broaden the types of evidence that can be accepted.</p><p> </p><p>We are in the process of reviewing legal aid for domestic violence victims in private family law cases, and will announce the full extent of our proposals to Parliament in due course.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-04-18T15:19:25.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709032/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709032/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Legal Aid Scheme: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 65872, on domestic violence and legal aid, by what means the Government announced its intention to completely remove the time limit on all forms of evidence and to broaden evidence types; when those proposals will come into effect; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","66948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709033","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-13","<p>The information requested at (a) – (c) is published in the Tribunals and Gender Recognition Certificate Statistics Quarterly on gov.uk at the following: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2016</a>.</p><p> </p><p>HMCTS only holds management information on costs awarded since September 2014. In the period September 2014 to August 2016 (the last two complete years of the published annual statistics) costs were awarded in 12 of the autistic spectrum disorder cases determined at hearing.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-13T12:48:50.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709033/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709033/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Special Educational Needs: Tribunals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many special educational needs and disability appeals for children with autistic spectrum disorder were (a) decided, (b) withdrawn and (c) granted in the last five years; and what costs were awarded in respect of those appeals.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","66960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709034","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-14","<p>The Government has repeatedly made clear that it is committed to commencing section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015 and will do so imminently.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-14T17:14:05.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709034/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709034/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to her Answer to the Topical Question from the hon. Member for Sheffield, Heeley of 7 March 2017, Official Report, if she will provide a timescale for when she plans to commence Section 67 of the Serious Crime Act 2015.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","66927"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709035","Home Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>This information is not held centrally, but is available from police forces.</p><p>Decisions about the most effective use of available resources, including the number of custody suites in a force area, are a matter for the Police and Crime Commissioner and Chief Constable locally (the Mayor’s Office for Policing and Crime and the Commissioner in the case of the Metropolitan Police and the Corporation and the Commissioner in the case of the City of London Police), tailored to the operational needs of the police in their local community.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-03-15T16:40:50.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709035/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709035/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-07","Police Custody: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many custody suites have been closed since 2010.","false","Biography information for Yasmin Qureshi","Bolton South East","Yasmin Qureshi","66979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709036","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-14","<p>The information requested is set out below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong> </strong> <strong>Average waiting time in weeks for the disposal of Personal Independence Payment </strong><sup>1</sup> <strong> appeals from receipt to outcome</strong><strong><sup>2</sup></strong> <strong>for the last four quarterly periods (January – December 2016) </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Doncaster </strong><strong><sup>3</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January – March 2016</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April – June 2016</p></td><td><p>19</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July – September 2016</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October – December 2016</p></td><td><p>15</p></td><td><p>16</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>SSCS data are attributed to the hearing venue nearest to the appellant’s home address. If the case goes to an oral hearing, the location of the Tribunal hearing venue is normally nearest to the appellant’s home address. We cannot retrieve data based on the appellants actual address, but can produce reports detailing the numbers of cases that were dealt with at one of our Regional centres or heard at a specific venue.</p><p> </p><p><sub>1</sub> Personal Independence Payment (New Claim Appeals), which replaced Disability Living Allowance and was introduced on 8 April 2013, also includes Personal Independence Claims (Reassessments).</p><p><sub>2 </sub>Outcome: All appeals disposed of include those appeals disposed of with and without a tribunal hearing.</p><p><sub>3 </sub>Covers all appeals heard at the Doncaster Venue which serves appellants living in Scunthorpe.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-14T17:12:29.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709036/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709036/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average waiting time is for an appeal against a mandatory reconsideration of a decision on personal independence payments in (a) Scunthorpe and (b) England for the last four periods for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","66786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709037","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Ministry of Justice participates in a variety of cross-government initiatives which allow participants to conduct short unpaid work experience.</p><p> </p><p>The Civil Service Work Experience Programme, formerly known as the Whitehall Internship Programme, lasts one to three weeks. We are preparing to host forty five students this year. The scheme welcomes participants from a socially deprived background with the intent to encourage them to consider a civil service career. The following table illustrates the total number of participants since 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Participants – Total number per year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>17</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Movement to Work Scheme, which lasts four to six weeks, is designed to meet the needs of 16-24 year olds not currently in education, employment or training. It helps participants in gaining valuable skills, experience in the workplace and improves their employment prospects. Details regarding the scheme are maintained by the Department for Work and Pensions.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-03-15T16:40:21.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709037/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709037/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Ministry of Justice: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in her Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709038","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>Where offenders are not complying with their sentences probation providers must take swift and robust action, with offenders returned to court for breach proceedings where appropriate. All enforcement procedures are set out in Probation Instructions and both CRCs and the NPS must follow the practice specified in mandatory actions within these.</p><p> </p><p>Data on missed appointments by offenders are not collected centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","66818","2017-03-15T17:56:29.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709038/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709038/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Wales Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what instructions are given to staff of the Community Rehabilitation Company in Wales to be followed when an offender under supervision misses three or more appointments without good reason.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","66822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709039","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>All CRCs are required by their contracts to make sure they have sufficient appropriately-qualified staff to deliver contractual services.</p><p> </p><p>The Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) in Wales has given assurance that it has met its obligations under the terms of the Enhanced Voluntary Redundancy scheme, which was used between October 2015 and July 2016. A separate and distinct Voluntary Severance Scheme has since been offered by employee agreement, allowing the CRC to offer terms to a greater number of staff.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","66823","2017-03-15T17:55:58.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709039/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709039/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Wales Community Rehabilitation Company: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reasons the Enhanced Voluntary Redundancy scheme was withdrawn by the Community Rehabilitation Company in Wales and replaced by a severance scheme; and what assessment she has made of the financial effects of that change on employees.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","66817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709041","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>Where offenders are not complying with their sentences probation providers must take swift and robust action, with offenders returned to court for breach proceedings where appropriate. All enforcement procedures are set out in Probation Instructions and both CRCs and the NPS must follow the practice specified in mandatory actions within these.</p><p> </p><p>Data on missed appointments by offenders are not collected centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","66822","2017-03-15T17:56:29.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709041/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709041/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Wales Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders under the supervision of the Community Rehabilitation Company in Wales missed eight appointments without good reason during 2015; and what steps were taken in each such case.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","66818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709043","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-16","<p>This information is not collected centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The Probation Service Review proposed that probation providers measure outcomes which include Housing, Education and Employment monitoring at specific key points throughout the offenders journey, including commencement and end of supervision periods. The measure is proposed for implementation in due course and guidance has been issued to inform recording practice to capture this data.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-16T16:57:55.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709043/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709043/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Wales Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people who were supervised by the Community Rehabilitation Company in Wales have entered paid employment or education following (a) supervision after completing a sentence of 12 months or less and (b) an interview with education and employment staff in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","66819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709044","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) in Wales was established on 1 June 2014. However, the statutory duty for CRCs to supervise offenders released into the community from custodial sentences of 12 months or less came into force with the Offender Rehabilitation Act on 1 February 2015. Between 1 February 2015 and 30 September 2016, 3,315 such offenders were released into supervision under Wales CRC.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-15T10:34:05.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709044/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709044/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Wales Community Rehabilitation Company","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many persons sentenced to 12 months or less have been supervised by the Community Rehabilitation Company in Wales since that Company was established.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","66820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709046","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-13","<p>We are investing £1.3bn to build up to 10,000 new prison places with better education facilities and other rehabilitative services. We will close down ageing and ineffective prisons, replacing them with buildings fit for today’s demands.</p><p> </p><p>The new prison development at HM Prison and Young Offender Institution Glen Parva will be suitable for category C male prisoners. Prisoners transferring to the new prison on the Glen Parva site may come from any appropriate prison in the estate depending on their personal and resettlement needs.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-13T11:44:19.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709046/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709046/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Prison Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether she has any plans to use the redeveloped Glen Parva Prison to accommodate prisoners from Leicester Prison when it is complete.","false","Biography information for Alberto Costa","South Leicestershire","Alberto Costa","66801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709047","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-24","<p>The Prime Minister's Office is an integral part of the Cabinet Office and is included in this reply.</p><p> </p><p>There is no centrally held record of unpaid work placements in the Cabinet Office. Therefore, it is not possible to provide information on the number of people that undertook an unpaid work placement in the department in each of the last five years. An attempt to do so would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","66889","2017-03-24T12:12:00.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709047/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709047/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-03-07","Prime Minister: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in 10 Downing Street in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709048","Scotland Office","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Scotland Office has had one unpaid work placement in each of the last 5 years, as part of the Whitehall Internship Programme. None of these placements lasted more than one month.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-03-15T12:57:30.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709048/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709048/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-03-07","Scotland Office: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709049","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-14","<p>The current increased penalties for drivers using mobile phones only came into effect on 1 March 2017. The Department will initiate work to allow for an assessment of the effectiveness of the penalties later this year.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-14T14:10:18.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709049/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709049/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of current penalties for drivers using mobile telephones.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","66781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709050","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-14","<p>The large majors programme is competitive and not every scheme will be funded so it is in Shropshire Council’s interest to submit a well evidenced and persuasive business case. Departmental officials have already met Council officers and will continue to provide advice on the development of the business case up to the point of submission to the Department. We will then make a decision on whether or not to provide funding for the construction of this scheme and any others submitted at the same time.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-14T13:54:47.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709050/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709050/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Roads: Shrewsbury","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that the business case for the North West Relief Road is conducted effectively and efficiently.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","66782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709051","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-13","<p>The data for all our SCS across the department is contained in the annex of the DfTc Equality Monitoring report. The reason for this is that, as SCS numbers in some of our agencies are small, individuals could possibly be identified by their diversity data if it were not all collated together. The data regarding DfT SCS disability is as follows.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Disability status</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p>Disabled</p></td><td><p>Non-Disabled</p></td><td><p>Unknown/Prefer not to say</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>% of SCS</p></td><td><p>2.5</p></td><td><p>66</p></td><td><p>31.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-13T13:17:15.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709051/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709051/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Department for Transport: Senior Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 6 March 2017 to Question 65566, where in the Department for Transport 2015-16 Equality Monitoring report the proportion of senior civil servants in his Department who are disabled is set out.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","66803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709052","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-15","<p>Motorists using jammers against police speed enforcement equipment already run the risk of being charged with perverting the course of justice, and there have been successful prosecutions.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-03-15T13:23:33.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709052/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709052/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Speed Limits: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he has taken to stop drivers using laser jammers to confuse or prevent speed cameras working properly.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709053","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department for Transport works closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on measures to address air pollution. We have established a Joint Air Quality Unit, staffed by members of both Departments, to develop and coordinate policy approaches.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-15T11:27:55.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709053/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709053/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent steps his Department has taken to assist the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs in reducing air pollution.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","66791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709054","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Government considered various options on how to support English regional airports against the impacts of Scottish devolution as part of the consultation “Options for supporting English regional impacts of air passenger duty devolution”. There was no stakeholder consensus for a structural change to the way that Air Passenger Duty (APD) is levied.</p><p> </p><p>The Government response to the consultation was published at Autumn Statement 2016. This indicated that the Government would keep the issue under review and would return to it once the UK leaves the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>Rates of APD are kept under review and the Chancellor announces any changes at fiscal events. Rates for 2019-20 will be set at Autumn Budget 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","66842 ; 66843 ; 66844","2017-03-15T13:58:59.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709054/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709054/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-07","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of devolving Air Passenger Duty to the Scottish Parliament on airports in the North of England.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","66841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709055","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Government considered various options on how to support English regional airports against the impacts of Scottish devolution as part of the consultation “Options for supporting English regional impacts of air passenger duty devolution”. There was no stakeholder consensus for a structural change to the way that Air Passenger Duty (APD) is levied.</p><p> </p><p>The Government response to the consultation was published at Autumn Statement 2016. This indicated that the Government would keep the issue under review and would return to it once the UK leaves the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>Rates of APD are kept under review and the Chancellor announces any changes at fiscal events. Rates for 2019-20 will be set at Autumn Budget 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","66841 ; 66843 ; 66844","2017-03-15T13:58:59.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709055/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709055/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-07","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to reduce Air Passenger Duty to match any reduction in that duty made by the Scottish Parliament  after April 2018.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","66842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709056","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Government considered various options on how to support English regional airports against the impacts of Scottish devolution as part of the consultation “Options for supporting English regional impacts of air passenger duty devolution”. There was no stakeholder consensus for a structural change to the way that Air Passenger Duty (APD) is levied.</p><p> </p><p>The Government response to the consultation was published at Autumn Statement 2016. This indicated that the Government would keep the issue under review and would return to it once the UK leaves the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>Rates of APD are kept under review and the Chancellor announces any changes at fiscal events. Rates for 2019-20 will be set at Autumn Budget 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","66841 ; 66842 ; 66844","2017-03-15T13:58:59.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709056/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709056/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-07","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will introduce a congestion based approach for Air Passenger Duty.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","66843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709057","HM Treasury","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Government considered various options on how to support English regional airports against the impacts of Scottish devolution as part of the consultation “Options for supporting English regional impacts of air passenger duty devolution”. There was no stakeholder consensus for a structural change to the way that Air Passenger Duty (APD) is levied.</p><p> </p><p>The Government response to the consultation was published at Autumn Statement 2016. This indicated that the Government would keep the issue under review and would return to it once the UK leaves the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>Rates of APD are kept under review and the Chancellor announces any changes at fiscal events. Rates for 2019-20 will be set at Autumn Budget 2017.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","66841 ; 66842 ; 66843","2017-03-15T13:58:59.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709057/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709057/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-03-07","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing a congestion based approach for Air Passenger Duty for airports in the North of England.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","66844"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709058","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-15","<p>The number of unpaid work placements undertaken in the Department are as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of Unpaid Work Placements</p></td><td><p>Number of Placements &gt; 1 Month</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>57</p></td><td><p>less than 5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>18</p></td><td><p>less than 5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>37</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>72</p></td><td><p>9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The work placements arise from a variety of different sources, for example working with local support agencies helping individuals who have had long term unemployment for various reasons, gain valuable work experience and build confidence to apply for future vacancies which may get them back into work; the Cabinet Office Whitehall internship scheme; and working with DWP and the Job Centre, on their Movement to Work programme, targeting 16-24 year olds who are unemployed and not in education.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-03-15T11:24:25.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709058/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709058/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Department for Transport: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709059","Department for Transport","false","2017-03-13","<p>Southern has created a new on-board supervisor (OBS) role for guards. These crew members are passenger-focussed and trained to manage emergencies.</p><p>Although operational staffing requirements are for the train operator to manage, the Department is aware that Southern will roster an on-board supervisor (OBS) on all trains which previously had a conductor. In addition, Southern has hired around 90 additional on-board supervisors and those staff are already working to assist passengers on Southern trains.</p><p /><p /> <p> </p><p /><p />","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-03-13T15:05:47.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709059/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709059/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-03-07","Southern: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with GTR-Southern on the adequacy of the number of on-board supervisors in their area of operation.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Quin","Horsham","Jeremy Quin","66934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709060","Wales Office","false","2017-03-13","<p><strong>The number of people who undertook unpaid work placements at the Wales Office in the last five years is set out below:</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Work Experience Pupils </strong> <strong>(one week)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Job Centre Plus placements</strong> <strong>(8 weeks)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Undergraduate University placements</strong> <strong>(more than one month)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>1*</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>* The duration of this placement was less than one month.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-03-13T10:47:14.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709060/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709060/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-03-07","Wales Office: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66905"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709061","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-15","<p>All CRCs are required by their contracts to make sure they have sufficient appropriately-qualified staff to deliver contractual services.</p><p> </p><p>The Community Rehabilitation Company (CRC) in Wales has given assurance that it has met its obligations under the terms of the Enhanced Voluntary Redundancy scheme, which was used between October 2015 and July 2016. A separate and distinct Voluntary Severance Scheme has since been offered by employee agreement, allowing the CRC to offer terms to a greater number of staff.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","66817","2017-03-15T17:55:58.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709061/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709061/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-07","Wales Community Rehabilitation Company: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Community Rehabilitation Company in Wales has met its obligations under the terms of the Enhanced Voluntary Redundancy scheme.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","66823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709062","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>The number of people on Universal Credit as of 12 January 2017 was 450,000.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-13T15:25:36.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709062/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709062/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people are in receipt of (a) live service universal credits and (b) full service universal credits.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","66808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709063","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>The information requested is currently not available.</p><p> </p><p>As outlined in the strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit, officials are currently assessing the data and will only release information once the necessary quality assurance work has taken place. These statistics will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for official statistics.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-13T15:22:06.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709063/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709063/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Universal Credit: Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many regular universal payments were not paid on time in (a) January and (b) February 2017.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","66807"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709064","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Government is always exploring new ways to support disabled people, including those making PIP appeals. We have had a range of discussions with Motability and other relevant departments, and any announcement regarding the progress of these discussions will be made publicly by the Government in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-15T14:16:27.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709064/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709064/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March 2017 to Question 64658, on personal independence payments, what options his Department is considering to better support disabled people with Motability vehicles who are waiting in excess of seven weeks for mandatory reconsiderations.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","66783"
