"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709068","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-14","<p>Marriage and civil partnerships are legal contracts that are associated with certain rights, including inheritance, recognition in the tax system and entitlement to certain benefits.</p><p> </p><p>A key principle of the National Insurance system is that all rights to benefits derived from another person’s contributions are based on the concept of legal marriage or civil partnership. This is a long-standing position in bereavement benefits which the Government has no plans to change.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-14T16:00:13.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709068/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709068/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Bereavement Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of extending widower's pension allowance to widowed partners who were (a) engaged and due to be married, (b) co-habiting and (c) co-habiting with children.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","66777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709069","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-15","<p>There is a wide range of exemptions from this policy which will ensure that vulnerable people are protected. As the policy will only apply to those who have no impediment to a return to the parental home I do not anticipate that there will be any impact on the levels of homelessness.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-15T17:07:05.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709069/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709069/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Housing Benefit: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of ending the automatic entitlement to housing benefit for 18 to 21 year-olds on the level of homelessness.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","66778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709070","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>Any evidence used to make a DWP decision that is still held by the Department, will be made available to the claimant on request by telephone, in writing or in person.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-13T13:42:58.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709070/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709070/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Social Security Benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how a person who has undergone an employment and support allowance or personal independence allowance assessment can obtain a copy of the relevant reports.","false","Biography information for Dr James Davies","Vale of Clwyd","Dr James Davies","66869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709071","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-15","<p>The following is a breakdown of the total number of people who started an unpaid work experience placement in DWP in each of the last 5 years and of these (where known), how many had an expected duration of 5 weeks or more. Our reporting is done by week rather than month:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total work experience starts</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Duration</strong> <strong>5 weeks + </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>*2012/13</p></td><td><p>1135</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>*2013/14</p></td><td><p>2623</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>7457</p></td><td><p>1016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>7583</p></td><td><p>1291</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>4183</p></td><td><p>63 (figures to the end of February 2017)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>*Placements in 2012/13 and 2013/14 were offered for a minimum of 4 weeks but could be extended to a maximum of 8 weeks. Figures broken down by length of placement are not available for this period.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-03-15T17:04:26.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709071/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709071/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Department for Work and Pensions: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66906"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709072","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>In line with the DWP data retention policy, any Personal Independence Payment documents or records that do not support any active award of benefit, are destroyed 2 years after the award ends or 2 years after a disallowance decision has been made. For ESA the retention period is 14 months following the end of the award or disallowance decision.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-03-13T13:41:27.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709072/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709072/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Sickness, disability and carers' benefits: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how long individual records of (a) personal independence allowance and (b) employment and support allowance assessments are held electronically before destruction.","false","Biography information for Dr James Davies","Vale of Clwyd","Dr James Davies","66870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709073","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>To receive a winter fuel payment a claimant has to have attained women’s State Pension age in or before the qualifying week which is the week beginning on the third Monday of September in that year.</p><p> </p><p>The attached link provides details of the relevant dates as women’s State Pension age increases until equalisation with men’s State Pension age in November 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Following equalisation entitlement to a winter fuel payment will be determined by having reached State Pension age in or before the September qualifying week.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/310231/spa-timetable.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/310231/spa-timetable.pdf</a>.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","66915","2017-03-13T13:50:12.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709073/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709073/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Winter Fuel Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria are used to set the birthday dates for winter fuel allowance allocation.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","66914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709074","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>To receive a winter fuel payment a claimant has to have attained women’s State Pension age in or before the qualifying week which is the week beginning on the third Monday of September in that year.</p><p> </p><p>The attached link provides details of the relevant dates as women’s State Pension age increases until equalisation with men’s State Pension age in November 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Following equalisation entitlement to a winter fuel payment will be determined by having reached State Pension age in or before the September qualifying week.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/310231/spa-timetable.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/310231/spa-timetable.pdf</a>.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","66914","2017-03-13T13:50:12.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709074/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709074/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Winter Fuel Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the birthday date for qualification for winter fuel allowance is planned to be for (a) men and (b) women in each of the next 15 years.","false","Biography information for Simon Hart","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart","66915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709075","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>We are currently considering our options for publication of the public consultation report for Bridgeton Jobcentre and will provide an update on likely timing in due course. Our priority, at present, is to review carefully the feedback we have received from our consultations.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-13T12:26:36.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709075/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709075/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date his Department plans to publish its response to the public consultation on proposals to close Bridgeton Jobcentre Plus in Glasgow.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","66950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709076","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-03-13","<p>The full details of when all Local Authorities and Jobcentres will roll out to Universal Credit is published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/571711/universal-credit-transition-rollout-schedule-phase-4-to-6-2017-to-2018.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/571711/universal-credit-transition-rollout-schedule-phase-4-to-6-2017-to-2018.pdf</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-03-13T15:19:50.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709076/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709076/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-03-07","Universal Credit: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when universal credit will be fully implemented in each local authority area in Wales.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","66963"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709077","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-09","<p>The Government is engaging across businesses, industry and other stakeholders on a range of issues relating to its plan for emissions reduction over the 2020s.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-09T11:04:55.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709077/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709077/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had on the title of the forthcoming emissions reduction plan.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","66821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709078","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) participates in centrally run and unpaid work placement schemes designed to promote social mobility and offer the opportunity to work shadow/gain work experience in the Civil Service. This continues practice in its legacy departments of Business, Innovation Skills (BIS) and Energy and Climate Change (DECC).</p><p>The schemes in question on which we can report numbers are:</p><ul><li>The Early Diversity Internship Programme, a work shadowing scheme offered to years 1-2 undergraduates, for a week at Easter</li><li>Civil Service Work Experience is for school students between the ages of 15 and 18. Placements are for less than 1 month based on school holidays.</li><li>Movement to Work to help 18-24 year olds into work, for 4-6 weeks. Job Seeker’s Allowance is still paid together with any travel costs.</li></ul><p>Since the formation of BEIS in July 2016, we have had 1 Movement to Work placement lasting for 6 weeks and 11 Civil Service Work Experience placements lasting less than one month.</p><p>Prior to the formation of BEIS, former BIS had 2 Early Diversity Internship Programme students in April 2016.</p><p>Available figures from legacy departments for Movement to Work and Civil Service Work Experience schemes for the previous 5 financial years are below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Dates</p></td><td><p>Total Number of unpaid placements</p></td><td><p>Number of placements lasting for longer than one month</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2015 to March 2016</p></td><td><p>Former BIS = 11</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2014 to March 2015</p></td><td><p>Former DECC = 1</p></td><td><p>Former DECC = 1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2013 to March 2014</p></td><td><p>Not available</p></td><td><p>Not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2012 to March 2013</p></td><td><p>Not available</p></td><td><p>Not available</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2011 to March 2012</p></td><td><p>Not available</p></td><td><p>Not available</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-15T10:58:50.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709078/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709078/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66887"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709079","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-13","<p>The design and implementation of the proposed competitive regime for onshore transmission assets is properly a matter for Ofgem as the independent regulator. It is important to note that, regardless of who constructs and maintains an asset, all network operators must be licenced by the regulator and are subject to strict controls to ensure safety, security and reliability. Any successful bidders will be held to the same strict standards that the current incumbent network companies operate by, including in regards to industry codes, grid standards and planning requirements.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-13T11:39:45.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709079/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709079/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","National Grid: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether successful bidders to construct any or all of the North West Coast Connection will be held to the same standards as National Grid on the (a) design and technology granted in the consent order, (b) levels of mitigation, such as undergrounding, (c) level of community and stakeholder engagement, (d) mitigating the environmental impacts, (e) impact of traffic and transport and (f) opportunities for local companies to form part of the construction supply chain.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","66832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709080","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-13","<p>The design and implementation of the proposed competitive regime for onshore transmission assets is properly a matter for Ofgem as the independent regulator. This would include any analysis or decision on whether to tender for competition any specific projects, including the North West Coast Connection. It is important to note that Ofgem has extensively consulted with industry on these proposals and intends to undertake an impact assessment on the case to tender all, or part, of the North West Coast Connection.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-13T11:39:24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709080/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709080/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","National Grid: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if a consumer-based, cost-benefit analysis has been undertaken on the potential benefits and disbenefits of completing all or part of the North West Coast Connection; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","66833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709081","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-13","<p>As a Nationally Significant Infrastructure Project, the proposed North West Coast Connection (NWCC) will require development consent under the Planning Act 2008. This requires developers to carry out extensive consultation on their proposals including with local communities before any formal development consent application is submitted to the Planning Inspectorate. Local communities can also provide their views to the Planning Inspectorate during the examination of any formal application. Further information is available on the National Infrastructure Planning website:</p><p><a href="https://infrastructure.planninginspectorate.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://infrastructure.planninginspectorate.gov.uk/</a></p><p>The design and implementation of the proposed competitive regime for onshore transmission assets is properly a matter for Ofgem as the independent regulator. As part of Ofgem’s decision making process on whether to tender the NWCC project they have run an open consultation which has enabled stakeholders including local communities to put forward their views for consideration. If Ofgem decides to tender the project then this process will run in line with the rules ensuring fair and transparent procurement. It is important to note that regardless of who constructs and maintains an asset all network operators must be licenced by the regulator and are subject to strict controls to ensure safety, security and reliability.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-13T11:38:44.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709081/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709081/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","National Grid: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what influence and by what means communities in the North West will have in decision making over how and who progresses the construction of the North West Coast Connection.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","66831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709082","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-15","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has not made its own assessment of the above question.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence that present rates of decline in the extent of Arctic sea ice are not consistent with reasonably expected natural variability is synthesised in the 5<sup>th</sup> Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC AR5). Long-term records of Arctic sea ice extent in this report show that the decline from 1980 onwards lies outside of what would be expected from natural variability alone. IPCC AR5 reports high confidence that human influences are <em>very likely </em>(&gt;90% probability) to have contributed to the observed Arctic sea ice loss since 1980.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-15T15:30:30.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709082/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709082/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","Climate Change: Snow and Ice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of whether present rates of decline in the extent of Arctic sea ice are consistent with reasonably expected natural variability.","false","Biography information for Lord Lilley","Hitchin and Harpenden","Mr Peter Lilley","66793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709083","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has not made its own assessment of the above question.</p><p> </p><p>Evidence that present rates of decline in the extent of Arctic sea ice are not consistent with reasonably expected natural variability is synthesised in the 5<sup>th</sup> Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC AR5). Long-term records of Arctic sea ice extent in this report show that the decline from 1980 onwards lies outside of what would be expected from natural variability alone. IPCC AR5 reports high confidence that human influences are <em>very likely </em>(&gt;90% probability) to have contributed to the observed Arctic sea ice loss since 1980.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-03-15T15:28:27.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709083/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709083/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","Climate Change: Snow and Ice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information he holds on whether there are declines of snow or ice, other than of Arctic sea ice extent, that are inconsistent with reasonably expected natural variability.","false","Biography information for Lord Lilley","Hitchin and Harpenden","Mr Peter Lilley","66792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709085","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-13","<p>The British Business Bank (BBB) is a government-owned economic development bank. It manages the UK Government’s access to finance programmes for smaller businesses within a single commercially-minded institution. The Bank received State aid clearance to start operating in November 2014. Since this date, BBB has provided funding to the following businesses:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>St Helen's North</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Merseyside</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>North West</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UK</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>No of SMEs</p></td><td><p>34 (excl. ENABLE Funding)</p></td><td><p>466 (excl. Start-up Loans)</p></td><td><p>6,921</p></td><td><p>43,918</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-03-13T14:55:51.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709085/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709085/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-03-07","British Business Bank","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many businesses in (a) St Helens North, (b) Merseyside, (c) the North West and (d) the UK have received funding from the British Business Bank since its inception.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","66804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709086","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department for International Trade has regular discussions with the Nigerian Government, including on trade. The Prime Minister’s Trade Envoy to Nigeria has visited twice since the vote on the UK leaving the EU as part of HMG’s coordinated activity to promote our trade and prosperity priorities. We support British companies to export more to Nigeria, to grow the bilateral trade relationship (worth $2.5bn in 2016). We also work with the Nigerian Government and others to make the environment easier to do business in.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-15T16:22:14.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709086/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709086/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-07","Overseas Trade: Nigeria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions his Department has had with the Nigerian Government on trade between the UK and Nigeria since the vote on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","66813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709087","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Department for International Trade was created in July 2016, the transfer of functions order established DIT as a corporation sole on 9 November 2016.</p><p>The Department does not directly hold this information as the international trade advisers are employed by our Contractors in the English Regions, who have provided the information in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1<sup>st</sup> January 2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1<sup>st</sup> January 2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1<sup>st</sup> January 2016</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>No. of ITAs in post</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>270</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>291</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>279</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>No. of ITAs leaving post in year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>22</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>37</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>49</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>No. of ITAs starting in post in year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>35</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>36</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>22</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-13T16:02:36.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709087/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709087/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-07","Trade Promotion: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the turnover rate was for international trade advisers in his Department in (a) 2014, (b) 2015 and (c) 2016.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","66857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709088","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Exporting is GREAT website has received over 700,000 unique visitors since launch in November 2015, resulting in over 74,000 applications for export opportunities.</p><p>The Department for International Trade is currently evaluating the Export Opportunities service. This includes working with HMRC data via the tax return system to determine the definitive number of businesses who export through the service and the resulting export value.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-03-13T17:53:22.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709088/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709088/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-07","Exports: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the (a) click-through rates to export opportunities and (b) conversion rate to exporters was for the Exporting is Great website in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","66858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709089","Department for International Trade","false","2017-03-15","<p>The Department for International Trade was created in July 2016 and became a legal employer as of 9 November 2016. We do not hold information on how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in the Department and to generate this information would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>UK Export Finance has had no unpaid work placements in each of the last five years.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-03-15T16:35:31.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709089/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709089/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-03-07","Department for International Trade: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709090","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-15","<p>As a new department, DExEU is not in a position to report on the use of unpaid work placements undertaken over the past 5 years. DExEU intends to make use of central Civil Service run schemes including the Summer Diversity Internship Programme, which is a paid two month placement, and the Early Diversity Internship Programme.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-15T15:33:47.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709090/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709090/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-07","Department for Exiting the European Union: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many people undertook an unpaid work placement in his Department in each of the last five years for which figures are available; and how many such placements lasted for longer than one month.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","66894"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709091","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-13","<p>Dates for the Joint Ministerial Committee are agreed by consensus across the four governments. Dates of JMC(EN) meetings are not usually publicised in advance.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-13T11:28:52.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709091/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709091/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-07","Devolution: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he will announce the future dates of Joint Ministerial Committee meetings with the devolved administrations on Exiting the EU between now and the triggering of Article 50.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","66931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709092","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-03-13","<p>We are committed to working closely with the Scottish Government, Welsh Government and Northern Ireland Executive to ensure that we get the best possible deal for all parts of the United Kingdom. This is exactly why we have set up a Joint Ministerial Committee on EU Negotiations, which brings together the UK Government and devolved administrations to develop a UK-wide approach. All of the devolved administrations have outlined to the Government their priorities for our future relationship with the EU. We welcome all proposals and are committed to carefully considering the options put forward. But we have been clear that no part of the UK will get a veto.<br><br></p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-03-13T11:26:13.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709092/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709092/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-03-07","Devolution: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he plans to establish an agreed UK position involving the devolved administrations before triggering Article 50.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","66930"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709112","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>We are reviewing the report and its findings, but our position remains that individuals who have been found not to need protection and have exhausted all legal avenues in the UK are expected to take steps to leave the UK as soon as possible. If they do not, we will seek to enforce their removal.</p><p> </p><p>The Immigration Act 2016 (‘the Act’) includes measures to remove incentives for migrants to remain in the UK where they have no lawful basis for doing so.</p><p> </p><p>However, failed asylum seekers, including failed asylum seeking families may be eligible for ongoing support while there is a genuine obstacle to their departure. As now, what constitutes a genuine obstacle is expected to include non-receipt of a travel document or a medical reason why they cannot travel. We would to continue to expect failed asylum seekers to demonstrate they are taking all reasonable steps to leave the UK.</p><p> </p><p>We want to support those who genuinely need our protection, but also send out a very clear message to those who seek to use the system to gain an unfair immigration advantage.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-21T15:26:14.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709112/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709112/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709112/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-07","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answers by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 9 February (HL Deb cols 1860–1861) about unaccompanied child refugees, what is their response to the report by the British Red Cross <i>Can’t Stay, Can’t Go</i> concerning refused asylum seekers who cannot be returned.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709113","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>The government supports English for Speakers of Other Languages (ESOL) as part of its wider strategy to improve adult literacy in England, support integration and break down barriers to employment. As soon as adults are granted refugee status or humanitarian protection they become eligible for skills funding – including for ESOL courses - through a provider’s adult education budget. In addition to the existing funding, an additional £3 million was distributed to colleges and other providers that deliver to learners in the areas identified by the government as having the greatest ESOL need. All of the geographical areas cited by <em>Refugee Action</em> in its report have received additional funding in December 2016.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-03-21T15:27:03.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709113/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709113/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709113/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-07","English Language: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answers by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 9 February (HL Deb cols 1860–1861) about unaccompanied child refugees, what is their response to the report by Refugee Action <i>Locked out of learning</i>: <i>A snapshot of ESOL provision in England</i> concerning the waiting times to access English language classes faced by refugees.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709114","Home Office","false","2017-03-21","<p>We support the principle of family unity and have several routes for families to be reunited safely. Our family reunion policy allows a spouse or partner and children under the age of 18 of those granted refugee status or humanitarian protection in the UK to join them here, if they formed part of the family unit before the sponsor fled their country. We have granted around 23,000 family reunion visas over the last five years. The Government is also fully committed to the timely and efficient operation of the Dublin Regulation, including the family reunification provisions.</p><p>The Government works upstream with the aim to stem flows from Libya to Italy. The UK is contributing to the EU’s Operation Sophia, which to date has successfully saved over 31,000 lives in the Central Mediterranean. The UK government is providing a £7.5 million package of direct emergency humanitarian assistance – to tackle people smuggling, improve conditions in detention centres and support migrants and asylum seekers, including children, transiting through Libya.</p><p>We are working internationally to help prevent vulnerable people from becoming victims of modern-slavery and other forms of exploitation. The Prime Minister (PM) pledged £30m of official development assistance to protect and support victims of trafficking as well saving lives and offering long term solutions to refugees and migrants rescued at sea. The PM Taskforce is also making progress bringing the collective weight of Government to bear. We are already seeing progress in intelligence gathering and are developing our international strategy to tackle the threat overseas and deepen law enforcement cooperation. This will enable us to investigate, prosecute and otherwise disrupt the activity of slave-drivers and traffickers of human beings. We also work closely with Europol and Eurojust to facilitate cross-border operations and joint investigations with European law enforcement agencies. We will continue to engage closely with the Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner on the issues of human trafficking and exploitation.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","HL5872 ; HL5873","2017-03-21T15:29:01.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709114/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709114/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/709114/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-07","Refugees: Families","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answers by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 9 February (HL Deb cols 1860–1861) about unaccompanied child refugees, what is their response to the briefing note by the Refugee Council, Oxfam UK, the British Red Cross and Amnesty International UK <i>Together again: Reuniting refugee families in safety – what the UK can do</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL5871"
