"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707692","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-03-09","<p>The proportion of fee-paying schools visiting Parliament through Parliament's Education Service in each <em>academic</em> year since 2010 were as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Academic Year</p></td><td><p>Fee-paying Schools visiting</p></td><td><p>Total schools visiting</p></td><td><p>Fee-paying Schools as a % of total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>96</p></td><td><p>864</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>129</p></td><td><p>1043</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>171</p></td><td><p>1216</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>169</p></td><td><p>1305</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>181</p></td><td><p>1302</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>237</p></td><td><p>2223</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>279</p></td><td><p>2541</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1262</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>10494</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>12</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The proportion of fee-paying schools visiting Parliament through Parliament's Education Service in each <em>financial</em> year since 2010 were as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Fee-paying Schools visiting</p></td><td><p>Total Schools Visiting</p></td><td><p>Fee-paying Schools as a % of total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010/11</p></td><td><p>101</p></td><td><p>836</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/12</p></td><td><p>126</p></td><td><p>997</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>146</p></td><td><p>1126</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>173</p></td><td><p>1244</p></td><td><p>14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>165</p></td><td><p>1282</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>213</p></td><td><p>1781</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>267</p></td><td><p>2495</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>1191</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>9761</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>12</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>These figures represent the number of individual schools visiting, rather than the overall number of sessions each school has booked (each school can book up to four sessions in an academic year).</p><p>The totals for 2016/17 are based upon actual visits up until 03/03/2017. Figures for the remainder of the academic / financial year are based upon bookings received.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-03-09T11:12:36.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707692/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707692/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-03-03","Parliament: Educational Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what proportion of schools visiting Parliament through Parliament's Education Service were fee-paying schools in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","66503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707693","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-09","<p>There is a credible risk of four famines in 2017: South Sudan (where famine has already been declared), Nigeria, Yemen and Somalia. We assess that in Yemen and Somalia the situation is deteriorating, whilst in Nigeria the situation may be beginning to improve in areas that the international community can access. This assessment is based on data from a number of sources, and corroborated with global experts from a range of international agencies.</p><p>We have issued a call to action to the international community to step up their response; provided lifesaving treatment for acute malnutrition, food, water and emergency healthcare; and are working closely with other donors and partners to ensure a more efficient and effective response to the crises.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-09T17:23:54.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707693/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707693/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-03","Africa and Yemen: Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the risk of famine in (a) Nigeria, (b) Yemen and (c) Somalia.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","66506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707694","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-10","<p>The UN has appealed for US $1.6 billion for South Sudan. The UK was the first major donor to raise the alarm bell and respond, committing £100m to the appeal on 22 February. We announced our funding early in order to amplify the urgency and encourage others to make contributions. I have publicly called for other international donors and the UN and World Bank to swiftly follow our lead.</p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-10T14:15:21.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707694/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707694/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-03","South Sudan: Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how her Department is working with other international donors to ensure that sufficient funding is made available for a rapid and effective response to the famine in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","66427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707695","Department for International Development","false","2017-03-09","<p>DFID is supporting high-impact nutrition interventions as part of our response in Yemen, South Sudan, Nigeria and Somalia, and in many other countries where malnutrition remains of concern. This includes treatment for acute malnutrition and support for safe infant and young child feeding. In all four famine-risk countries, nutrition interventions are being provided alongside other services, such as food assistance, essential health support and provision of water, sanitation and hygiene services to help address the causes of malnutrition and to help avert famine.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-03-09T17:25:16.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707695/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707695/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-03-03","Developing Countries: Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how her Department plans to provide more high-impact nutrition interventions as a means of preventing famine.","false","Biography information for Patrick Grady","Glasgow North","Patrick Grady","66428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707696","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-13","<p>The Government respects and values the role of the independent Prison Service Pay Review Body (PSPRB) as a compensatory mechanism for Operational staff within the Prison Service for whom the inducement to participate in industrial action is prohibited by law.</p><p> </p><p>The PSPRB members are independently appointed through the Public Appointments Team and the panel makes independent recommendations having considered evidence from both NOMS, in agreement with wider Government, and trade unions.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-03-13T18:05:46.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707696/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707696/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-03","Prison Officers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps she plans to take to ensure the independence of the Prison Officers' Pay Review Body from (a) prison service management and (b) Government.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","66425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707697","Home Office","false","2017-03-29","<p>The current published data for returns of foreign national offenders can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/593036/returns5-q4-2016-tables.ods</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-03-29T15:28:44.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707697/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707697/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-03-03","Offenders: Deportation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of prisoners recommended for deportation have been (i) deported and (ii) released and not deported in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","66491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707698","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-03-13","<p>The number of defendants proceeded against at magistrates’ courts for offences specifically under the Modern Slavery Act 2015 in England and Wales in 2015 can be found in the ‘Criminal Justice Statistics Quarterly: December 2015’ on Gov.uk</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Data for calendar year 2016 is planned for publication in May 2017.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-03-13T12:53:53.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707698/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/707698/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-03-03","Modern Slavery Act 2015: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been prosecuted for offences under the Modern Slavery Act 2015 since that legislation came into force.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","66482"
